  "Idea": "Current kNN-MT systems rely heavily on the continuous hidden representations generated by the neural MT model during inference to retrieve relevant translation examples from a large datastore. While effective, this approach often treats the source sentence as a black-box input, neglecting explicit, discrete linguistic structures that could enhance retrieval precision. Our proposed idea, 'Source-Driven Retrieval in kNN-MT', introduces a dual-path retrieval framework where the standard vector-based similarity search is augmented with a structured, source-side feature matcher that leverages parsed linguistic and semantic attributes of the input sentence. Specifically, we extract and encode multiple layers of source-side information—including dependency parse trees, semantic role labels, named entity types, part-of-speech tags, and discourse connectives—and use them to compute a structured similarity score between the input and datastore entries. This structured score is then combined with the standard embedding-based similarity (e.g., FAISS) via a learnable fusion mechanism to re-rank candidate neighbors. By doing so, the system prioritizes examples that are not only semantically close in vector space but also structurally analogous in terms of syntax and meaning. For instance, when translating a complex sentence with a passive construction and medical terminology, the system would preferentially retrieve other passive-voice medical sentences, even if their raw embeddings are slightly less similar. We further propose a cooperative training regime where the fusion weights are optimized using contrastive learning between positive (structurally + semantically aligned) and negative (misaligned) example pairs. This ensures that the retrieval becomes increasingly sensitive to linguistically grounded patterns. The impact of this approach lies in its ability to improve translation consistency, especially for low-frequency syntactic constructions and domain-specific 